patients had initial gadolinium enhancement (A: 15.6%; B: 36.8% as grade II, 95% 
as grade III; C: 90%), generally associated with MIBI hypermetabolism (p < 
0.0001). Survival rates at 2, 5, and 10 years were A: 88%, 88%, 85%; B: 79%, 
64%, 42%; C: 43%, 16%, 15%.
CONCLUSIONS: Secondary anaplastic oligodendroglioma patients were younger than 
patients with de novo anaplastic oligodendrogliomas. Histologic confirmation is 
mandatory because some low grade oligodendrogliomas had gadolinium enhancement 
on MRI and some anaplastic did not. Survival time was longer for secondary than 
for de novo anaplastic oligodendrogliomas without difference in the duration of 
the malignant phase of the disease.

